This is an alternative that uses the (really powerful) Java Streams API.
For your case, the [`Collectors.joining()`](https://docs.oracle.com/javase/8/docs/api/java/util/stream/Collectors.html) method comes in handy. It only inserts delimiters between elements, so by default you don&#39;t get the trailing comma.

```java
void writeMatrix(String filename, int[][] matrix) {
  try {
    BufferedWriter bw = new BufferedWriter(new FileWriter(filename));

    for (int[] row: matrix) {
      String rowString = Arrays.stream(row)
          .boxed()
          .map(Objects::toString)
          .collect(Collectors.joining(&quot;,&quot;));
      bw.write(rowString);
      bw.newLine();
    }

    bw.flush();
  } catch (IOException e) {}
}
```

Note: you could replace the outer `for` loop with another Streams API call: take a look at `forEach` in the [docs](https://docs.oracle.com/javase/8/docs/api/java/util/stream/Stream.html). And there are many examples you can find online too.

```java
void writeMatrix(String filename, int[][] matrix) {
  String matrixString = Arrays.stream(matrix).map(row -&gt;
      Arrays.stream(row)
          .boxed()
          .map(Objects::toString)
          .collect(Collectors.joining(&quot;,&quot;))
      )
      .collect(Collectors.joining(&quot;\n&quot;));

  try {
    BufferedWriter bw = new BufferedWriter(new FileWriter(filename));
    bw.write(matrixString);
    bw.flush();
  } catch (IOException e) {}
}
```

The Streams API is really elegant. The only issue you might find with this implementation is a stack overflow (excuse the pun :)) if the matrix is too large.

